article.description: Stephanie Higgs scored 16 points Friday night to lead the Yellow Jackets to a 55-49 upset of No. 6 Georgia, which lost to its state rival for the second time in three years.
article.headline: Poor shooting sinks Lady Dawgs
article.linkText: Georgia Tech knocks off No. 6 Georgia
article.story:
ATLANTA (AP) -- Georgia Tech has finally turned its series against Georgia into a real rivalry.

Stephanie Higgs scored 16 points Friday night to lead the Yellow Jackets to a 55-49 upset of No. 6 Georgia, which lost to its state rival for the second time in three years.

"I would think this is a statement game for us," Georgia Tech coach MaChelle Joseph said. "We just beat an opponent that was ranked sixth in the nation."

Georgia Tech (4-0) has claimed the upper hand in a series it trails 25-2. The Yellow Jackets lost their first 24 games against Georgia before breaking through two years ago with a 65-61 victory at nearby Philips Arena.

They proved it wasn't a fluke, beating their highest-ranked opponent since a victory over No. 4 Maryland in 1992.

"To beat Georgia on our home court for the first time at least makes a statement in the state that this rivalry is for real," Joseph said. "I just hope for my kids that it gives them the confidence to know they can compete with anyone in the country."

Georgia (5-2) had no chance of winning with shooting like this -- 20-of-69 from the field (29 percent) and just 2-of-16 from beyond the 3-point arc.

"Offensively, we're an embarrassment," said coach Andy Landers, whose team lost for the second time in a week. "Why we didn't try to exploit them, make them play a little more defense? But if that's what the players want to do, we'll consistently get our butts beat."

The Lady Bulldogs looked impressive in a victory over then-No. 2 Texas but have lost twice against unranked opponents. Last Saturday, they fell 64-63 to Texas Christian in Hawaii, though TCU has now moved into the Top 25.

Georgia's freshman star, Tasha Humphrey, was hampered by an ankle injury and didn't start for the first time. She managed only six points -- nine below her average -- on 2-of-7 shooting.

The Yellow Jackets collapsed on Humphrey when she touched the ball. She was constantly harassed by two players, and sometimes a third would drop back on the freshman.

"The ankle is fine," Humphrey said. "I just forced a lot of shots and didn't kick out the ball when I needed to."

Not that she got a lot of help from Georgia's three-guard lineup. Sherill Baker, Cori Chambers and Alexis Kendrick combined to go 10-of-43.

Another guard, Janese Hardrick, didn't play because of an ankle injury. Rebecca Rowsey, with 12 points, was the lone Georgia player in double figures.

Landers tried all sort of tactics to spark his team. He yelled and stomped his feet. At one point, he flopped down in his chair, feigning indifference to what was happening in front of him.

Afterward, he was more concerned about the state of his team than losing to a state rival.

"I don't even have time to think about that," Landers said. "I've got a basketball team that's sick."

Georgia Tech scored the final seven points of the first half for a 27-23 lead at the break. Janie Mitchell hit a 3-pointer, Higgs scored on a baseline drive and Daphne Mitchell beat the buzzer with a 10-footer jumper.

The Yellow Jackets charged off the court, pumping fists defiantly as they headed to the locker room with the momentum clearly on their side.

It carried over to the second half. Georgia Tech scored the first three baskets to lead 33-23. Chambers finally broke through, scoring Georgia's first basket on a jumper nearly three minutes in.

Georgia Tech built the lead to 13 points and Georgia never seriously challenged, even though the Yellow Jackets shot a mere 32 percent.

"We didn't shoot the ball well. Georgia didn't shoot the ball well," Joseph said. "But both teams battled, and our team won out on hustle points."

The Lady Bulldogs were playing on the Georgia Tech campus for the first time since 1988. The teams have played once in Athens and eight times at neutral sites over the past 16 years.

"It's really special, especially to beat them at home," Joseph said. "We didn't even talk about being afraid."
